:"1120","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1062":"1062","1084":"1084","1082":"1082","1060":"1060","1 August 1080":"1 augustus 1080","1106":"1106","1124":"1124","1078":"1078","1 February 1120":"1 februari 1120","about 1100":"circa 1100","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England":"Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Holderness, Yorkshire, England, UK":"Holderness, Yorkshire, England","Holderness, Yorkshire, England":"Holderness, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire North Riding, England":"Yorkshire North Riding, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1 August 1080–1 February 1120":"1 August 1080–1 February 1120","1080–1120":"1080–1120","1084–1124":"1084–1124","1106–1186":"1106–1186","1060–1120":"1060–1120","1062–1082":"1062–1082","1080":"1080","1186":"1186","1120":"1120","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1062":"1062","1084":"1084","1082":"1082","1060":"1060","1 August 1080":"1 August 1080","1106":"1106","1124":"1124","1078":"1078","1 February 1120":"1 February 1120","about 1100":"about 1100","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England":"Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Holderness, Yorkshire, England, UK":"Holderness, Yorkshire, England","Holderness, Yorkshire, England":"Holderness, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire North Riding, England":"Yorkshire North Riding, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bisset","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Bissett  .","French: from a diminutive of Old French <i>bisse</i> ‘fine linen’ (see   Bisson  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Bissett","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>biset</i> ‘dark’, a diminutive of <i>bis</i> (see   Biss  ).","Altered form of French <b>Bizet</b>: nickname for someone with a dark complexion, derived from <i>bis</i> ‘grayish-brown’. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>. Compare   Bissette  .","History: The surname <i>Bissett</i> (see 1 above) was brought to Scotland from Nottinghamshire <i>c.</i> 1175 by Henricus Byset, an Englishman who became a retainer of King William the Lion. — It was Jean George Bizet from Haute-Saône, France, whose surname was changed to <i>Bissett</i> (see 2 above) after his immigration to NS, Canada, in 1752."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":5,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":15,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":25,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Henry de Bisset was born on 1 August 1080, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Bartholomew Biset, was 20 and his mother, Abigail de Yorkshire, was 18. He married Bertha de Bridgeford about 1100, in Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 1 February 1120, in Holderness, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1 August 1080–1 February 1120":"1. august 1080–1. veebruar 1120","1080–1120":"1080–1120","1084–1124":"1084–1124","1106–1186":"1106–1186","1060–1120":"1060–1120","1062–1082":"1062–1082","1080":"1080","1186":"1186","1120":"1120","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1062":"1062","1084":"1084","1082":"1082","1060":"1060","1 August 1080":"1. august 1080","1106":"1106","1124":"1124","1078":"1078","1 February 1120":"1. veebruar 1120","about 1100":"umbes 1100","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England":"Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Holderness, Yorkshire, England, UK":"Holderness, Yorkshire, England","Holderness, Yorkshire, Eng